A: You must first consider, that you can not get any better time complexity than O(n log n) in the general case.
In you case the number of elements is limited to 10^5 which means that you have to get down to the order O(n) with only one loop.
For that you can try the following:
  int tmp;
  for (int i = 0; i < 10E6; i++)  // you should not use magic numbers as they are hard to maintain
  {
    tmp = i;
    for(j = 0; j < n; j++)
    {
      if(i == nums[j])
      {
        tmp = -1;
        break;
      }
      if(tmp < nums[j] && i != nums[j])
      {
        i = j;
      }
    }
  }

For a number i the program takes the following steps to find a proper position:

*

*set the first pointer j to zero

*check if i is equal to the element nums[j] if so set tmp to -1 and break to the next cycle.

*if the tmp value is still above 0 iterate j untill it's smaller than the tmp value and is bigger than the value of the current element.

*if the previous check passes set tmp to j

*if j is equal to n do nothing - which means it would be on the last position.

*if the previous if was not fulfilled set i to j and go back to cycle 1 to continue searching.

With this logic you get the algorithm you need with O(n), because n is limited to 1000000 and the check on tmp should take constant time.
I tested it with 1000000 values as well and it worked.
Note: The above algorithm has one serious issue: The following input will fail: 1000, 1000, 2000, 1000, 1000, 1000, 2000 It would result in the following output: 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000
If you need the algorithm sorted in multiple passes with the first pass finding the position of the smallest digit use quicksort with O(n log n), then quicksort with O(n), ...

A: If you cannot use built-ins and you have to go lower than O(N logN) then you might be able to use merge sort:
For each 1000 element block, sort it with quicksort (your function with O(N logN)) and compare the 500th element to the same element at the same position in the other sorted block: if the other is bigger then the first block, the first block is smaller then your first element. Otherwise the second block is smaller. If you always chose that block then you have an ascending sorting algorithm with O(N).

