A: This behavior is a result of the CPU's prefetch logic.
On nearly all modern CPUs, the hardware fetches some data into cache without being explicitly told to do so — it will do it as the code executes, when it sees it could help the performance of the running code. This is known as the processor's prefetch logic, and it's one of the big ways that makes CPU micro-architecture significantly more complex than a simple RISC (e.g. ARM) or CISC (e.g. x86) one.
The details behind this differ significantly between processors. It's most obvious when you're doing two separate accesses to your data, but it can do things like automatically prefetch larger chunks of data when you ask it to access a particular set of addresses repeatedly.
In practice, it's almost always better to sort your data if it's ever going to be accessed this way and you know that it will help out the timing; otherwise, you could be running this loop a billion times, but still only get the first chunk of your data "out on the bus" to the processor — which is a very slow operation in itself — half a dozen times before the next one comes in.
The specifics of how much of the difference is attributable to the prefetch logic will vary with the processor, but it is usually on the order of a few percent or less.

