A: The difference in times you observe is due to how your primary loop works. The loop:
for (unsigned c = 0; c < arraySize; ++c)
{   // Primary loop.
    if (data[c] >= 128)
        sum += data[c];
}

Will be unrolled by the compiler. A possible unrolling could look like:
for (unsigned c = 0; c < arraySize / 4; ++c)
{// Primary loop.
    __m256i x = _mm256_loadu_si256((__m256i*)&data[c * 4]); //load 256 bits of data (4 * 64 bits = 256 bits)

    __m256i lo_cmp = _mm256_set1_epi8(128); //create an 256-bit register with all comparison data. The number 128 will be compared with each data.
                                                //set 1_epi8 makes 1 element of an 256-bit register. You might want to change that depending on how the data is defined.        
    __m256i mask = _mm256_cmpgt_epi8(x, lo_cmp); //make the mask. Elements are selected based on a comparison between 2 numbers. If the element meets the comparison, it will be selected and put into another register. If not, it will be unselected.
    x = _mm256_and_si256(x, mask); //use the comparison mask to select data. For example if x = {128, 127, 126, 0, 4, 523, 829, 0} and lo_cmp = {128, 128, 128, 128, 128, 128, 128, 128], then x is changed to be x = {0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 523, 0} based on the mask
    sum += _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[0] + _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[1] + _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[2] + _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[3]; //compute the sum by converting each data into 32-bit integers and summing all of this.
    sum += _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[4] + _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[5] + _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[6] + _mm256_cvtepi8_epi32(x)[7]; //do the same thing.
}

As you can see, your primary loop is unrolled 4 times by the compiler. The sum is computed by 4 parallel registers, each containing 8 bytes and doing a cmp(x[i], 128). That is why the data must be aligned to 256 bits or the compiler does not unroll the loop.
However, the sorted data is now different:
for (unsigned c = 0; c < arraySize; ++c)
{   // Primary loop.
    if (data[c] >= 128)
        sum += data[c];
}

becomes
for (unsigned c = 0; c < arraySize; ++c) //this means that the following block is executed once for each iteration but since data is sorted arraySize might change so data[c] might not be aligned with data[c + 1] anymore making an alignment problem.
{   // Primary loop.
    if (data[c] >= 128)
    {
        if (data[c] >= 128)
        {
            if (data[c] >= 128)
            {
                if (data[c] >= 128)
                    sum += data[c];
            }
        }
    }
}

For larger array sizes, for example 32 elements, the data would not need to be aligned anymore but the compiler is unrolling the loop only once or twice instead of the expected 8 times. It seems that the sorted data has some really nice locality now and the cache can store more data without having to discard previous data.
This behavior is different for xmm and ymm registers, where the compiler does not perform any kind of optimization with unaligned data. Using this function to make sure both data are aligned will improve the code slightly but will take at least half the time we had before.
So it is not the sorting, it is all about how the optimization works.

